name: Sean Farmer
tweet: 14/ So why am I laying out all this? Simple. We were a state agency who implemented these policies to address excessive use of force.  Our residents were far stronger and much more likely to attack us than nearly any a police officer is likely to encounter.

name: Sean Farmer
tweet: 13/ #8cantwait  “Require all force be reported”  If we failed to report any incident we were immediately removed from duty. Failure to reporter incorrect  use of force would result in criminal charges levied against us.   The residents had an official advocate that saw to that.

name: Sean Farmer
tweet: 8/ When you have a multilevel use of force your allowing room for people to misunderstand or justify. Use of force should be kept as simple as possible.  For us there were only 2 uses of force allowed: redirection and takedowns.

name: Sean Farmer
tweet: 7/ #8cantwait  “Establish use of force continuum”  This was the most important part of our training. And the point that people may not agree with me on.   Because I don’t think it’s a good idea in practice. And will likely make everything worse.

name: Sean Farmer
tweet: 6/ #8cantwait  “Require warning before shooting”  If a situation continued to escalate, and the use of force was becoming a reality we made sure the resident knew that.  2 warnings, with time to comply. Usually 15 seconds. No 3rd warning like people expect.
